# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linux-capabilities
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] A capability-based system, in contrast, is designed with that goal in mind.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Capabilities achieve their objective of improving system security by being used in place of forgeable references.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] A forgeable reference (for example, a path name) identifies an object, but does not specify which access rights are appropriate for that object and the user program which holds that reference.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Consequently, any attempt to access the referenced object must be validated by the operating system, based on the ambient authority of the requesting program, typically via the use of an access-control list (ACL).
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Instead, in a system with capabilities, the mere fact that a user program possesses that capability entitles it to use the referenced object in accordance with the rights that are specified by that capability.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In theory, a system with capabilities removes the need for any access control list or similar mechanism by giving all entities all and only the capabilities they will actually need.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] A capability is typically implemented as a privileged data structure that consists of a section that specifies access rights, and a section that uniquely identifies the object to be accessed.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] The user does not access the data structure or object directly, but instead via a handle.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In practice, it is used much like a file descriptor in a traditional operating system (a traditional handle), but to access every object on the system.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Capabilities are typically stored by the operating system in a list, with some mechanism in place to prevent the program from directly modifying the contents of the capability (so as to forge access rights or change the object it points to).
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Some systems have also been based on capability-based addressing (hardware support for capabilities), such as Plessey System 250.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Programs possessing capabilities can perform functions on them, such as passing them on to other programs, converting them to a less-privileged version, or deleting them.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] The operating system must ensure that only specific operations can occur to the capabilities in the system, in order to maintain the integrity of the security policy.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Capabilities as discussed in this article should not be confused with Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) 1e/2c "Capabilities".
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] The latter are coarse-grained privileges that cannot be transferred between processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] A capability is defined to be a protected object reference which, by virtue of its possession by a user process, grants that process the capability (hence the name) to interact with an object in certain ways.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Those ways might include reading data associated with an object, modifying the object, executing the data in the object as a process, and other conceivable access rights.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] The capability logically consists of a reference that uniquely identifies a particular object and a set of one or more of these rights.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Although this identifies a unique object on the system, it does not specify access rights and hence is not a capability.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] This pair identifies an object along with a set of access rights.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] The pair, however, is still not a capability because the user process's *possession* of these values says nothing about whether that access would actually be legitimate.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] The variable `fd` now contains the index of a file descriptor in the process's file descriptor table.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Its existence in the process's file descriptor table is sufficient to show that the process does indeed have legitimate access to the object.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] A key feature of this arrangement is that the file descriptor table is in kernel memory and cannot be directly manipulated by the user program.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In traditional operating systems, programs often communicate with each other and with storage using references like those in the first two examples.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Path names are often passed as command-line parameters, sent via sockets, and stored on disk.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] These references are not capabilities, and must be validated before they can be used.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In these systems, a central question is "on whose *authority* is a given reference to be evaluated?" This becomes a critical issue especially for processes which must act on behalf of two different authority-bearing entities.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] They become susceptible to a programming error known as the confused deputy problem, very frequently resulting in a security hole.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In a capability-based system, the capabilities themselves are passed between processes and storage using a mechanism that is known by the operating system to maintain the integrity of those capabilities.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] One novel approach to solving this problem involves the use of an orthogonally persistent operating system.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In such a system, there is no need for entities to be discarded and their capabilities be invalidated, and hence require an ACL-like mechanism to restore those capabilities at a later time.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] The operating system maintains the integrity and security of the capabilities contained within all storage, both volatile and nonvolatile, at all times; in part by performing all serialization tasks by itself, rather than requiring user programs to do so, as is the case in most operating systems.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Because user programs are relieved of this responsibility, there is no need to trust them to reproduce only legal capabilities, nor to validate requests for access using an access control mechanism.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] An example implementation is the Flex machine from the early 1980s.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) draft 1003.1e specifies a concept of permissions called "capabilities".
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] However, POSIX capabilities differ from capabilities in this article.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] A POSIX capability is not associated with any object; a process having CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE capability can listen on any TCP port under 1024.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In contrast, Capsicum Unix hybridizes a true capability-system model with a Unix design and POSIX API.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] Capsicum capabilities are a refined form of file descriptor, a delegable right between processes and additional object types beyond classic POSIX, such as processes, can be referenced via capabilities.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] In Capsicum capability mode, processes are unable to utilize global namespaces (such as the filesystem namespace) to look up objects, and must instead inherit or be delegated them.
[src:linux-capabilities/capability-based-security] This system is found natively in FreeBSD, but patches are available to other systems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The **Linux kernel** is a free and open-source Unix-like kernel that is used in many computer systems worldwide.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991 and was soon adopted as the kernel for the GNU operating system (OS), which was created to be a free replacement for Unix.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Since the late 1990s, it has been included in many operating system distributions, many of which are called Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] One such Linux kernel operating system is Android, which is used in many mobile and embedded devices.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the kernel code is written in C as supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), which has extensions beyond standard C.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The code also contains assembly code for architecture-specific logic such as optimizing memory use and task execution.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel has a modular design such that modules can be integrated as software components – including dynamically loaded.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is monolithic in an architectural sense since the entire OS kernel runs in kernel space.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is provided under the GNU General Public License version 2, although it contains files under other compatible licenses.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 1991, Linus Torvalds was a computer science student enrolled at the University of Helsinki.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] During his time there, he began to develop an operating system as a side-project inspired by UNIX, for a personal computer.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] He started with a task switcher in Intel 80386 assembly language and a terminal driver.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] On 17 September 1991, Torvalds prepared version 0.01 of Linux and put on the "ftp.funet.fi" – FTP server of the Finnish University and Research Network (FUNET).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] It was not even executable since its code still needed Minix to compile and test it.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] On 5 October 1991, Torvalds announced the first "official" version of Linux, version 0.02.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] At the time, the GNU Project had completed many components for its free UNIX replacement, GNU, but its kernel, the GNU Hurd, was incomplete.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The project adopted the Linux kernel for its OS.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds labeled the kernel with major version 0 to indicate that it was not yet intended for general use.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.11, released in December 1991, was the first version to be self-hosted; compiled on a computer running the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] When Torvalds released version 0.12 in January 1992, he adopted the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2) over his previous self-drafted license, which had not permitted commercial redistribution.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In contrast to Unix, all Linux source files are freely available, including device drivers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The initial success of Linux was driven by programmers and testers across the world.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Because Linux implemented Unix-like system call semantics and exposed the standard POSIX APIs through an implementation of the C standard library, Linux could run software and applications that had been originally developed for Unix.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] On 19 January 1992, the first post to the new newsgroup *alt.os.linux* was submitted.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] On 31 March 1992, the newsgroup was renamed *comp.os.linux*.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The fact that Linux is a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a debate between Andrew S.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Tanenbaum, the creator of MINIX, and Torvalds.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate started in 1992 on the Usenet group *comp.os.minix* as a general discussion about kernel architectures.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.96 released in May 1992 was the first capable of running the X Window System.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In March 1994, Linux 1.0.0 was released with 176,250 lines of code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As indicated by the version number, it was the first version considered suitable for a production environment.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In June 1996, after release 1.3, Torvalds decided that Linux had evolved enough to warrant a new major number, and so labeled the next release as version 2.0.0.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Significant features of 2.0 included symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), support for more processors types and support for selecting specific hardware targets and for enabling architecture-specific features and optimizations.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The *make *config* family of commands of *kbuild* enable and configure options for building ad hoc kernel executables (vmlinux) and loadable modules.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.2, released on 20 January 1999, improved locking granularity and SMP management, added m68k, PowerPC, Sparc64, Alpha, and other 64-bit platforms support.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, it added new file systems including Microsoft's NTFS read-only capability.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 1999, IBM published its patches to the Linux 2.2.13 code for the support of the S/390 architecture.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.4.0, released on 4 January 2001, contained support for ISA Plug and Play, USB, and PC Cards.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Linux 2.4 added support for the Pentium 4 and Itanium (the latter introduced the ia64 ISA that was jointly developed by Intel and Hewlett-Packard to supersede the older PA-RISC), and for the newer 64-bit MIPS processor.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Development for 2.4.*x* changed a bit in that more features were made available throughout the series, including support for Bluetooth, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) version 1, RAID support, InterMezzo and ext3 file systems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.6.0 was released on 17 December 2003.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The development for 2.6.*x* changed further towards including new features throughout the series.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Starting with 2.6.x releases, the kernel supported a large number of file systems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Some were designed for Linux, like ext3, ext4, FUSE, and Btrfs.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Others were native to other operating systems like JFS, XFS, Minix, Xenix, Irix, Solaris, System V, Windows, and MS-DOS.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Though development had not used a version control system thus far, in 2002, Linux developers adopted BitKeeper, which was made freely available to them even though it was not free software.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005, because of efforts to reverse-engineer it, the company that owned the software revoked its support of the Linux community.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In response, Torvalds and others wrote Git.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The new system was written within weeks, and in two months the first official kernel made using it was released.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005 the *stable team* was formed as a response to the lack of a kernel tree where people could work on bug fixes, and it would keep updating *stable* versions.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In February 2008 the *linux-next* tree was created to serve as a place where patches aimed to be merged during the next development cycle gathered.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Several subsystem maintainers also adopted the suffix *-next* for trees containing code that they mean to submit for inclusion in the next release cycle.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As of January 2014, the in-development version of Linux is held in an unstable branch named *linux-next*.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The 20th anniversary of Linux was celebrated by Torvalds in July 2011 with the release of version 3.0.0.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As 2.6 had been the version number for 8 years, a new *uname26* personality that reports 3.x as 2.6.40+x had to be added to the kernel so that old programs would work.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.0 was released on 22 July 2011.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 May 2011, Torvalds announced that the big change was "NOTHING.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Absolutely nothing." and asked, "...let's make sure we really make the next release not just an all new shiny number, but a good kernel too." After the expected 6–7 weeks of the development process, it would be released near the 20th anniversary of Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The same series unified support for the ARM processor.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The numbering change from 2.6.39 to 3.0, and from 3.19 to 4.0, involved no meaningful technical differentiation; the major version number was increased simply to avoid large minor numbers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Stable 3.x.y kernels were released until 3.19 in February 2015.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.11, released on 2 September 2013, added many new features such as the new O_TMPFILE flag for `open(2)` to reduce temporary file vulnerabilities, experimental AMD Radeon dynamic power management, low-latency network polling, and zswap (compressed swap cache).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In April 2015, Torvalds released kernel version 4.0.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] By February 2015, Linux had received contributions from nearly 12,000 programmers from more than 1,200 companies, including some of the world's largest software and hardware vendors.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Version 4.1 of Linux, released in June 2015, contains over 19.5 million lines of code contributed by almost 14,000 programmers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] A total of 1,991 developers, of whom 334 were first-time collaborators, added more than 553,000 lines of code to version 5.8, breaking the record previously held by version 4.9.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] According to the Stack Overflow's annual Developer Survey of 2019, more than 53% of all respondents have developed software for Linux and about 27% for Android, although only about 25% develop with Linux-based operating systems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Most websites run on Linux-based operating systems, and all of the world's 500 most powerful supercomputers run on Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Linux distributions bundle the kernel with system software (e.g., the GNU C Library, systemd, and other Unix utilities and daemons) and a wide selection of application software, but their usage share in desktops is low in comparison to other operating systems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Android, which runs on a modified Linux kernel, accounts for the majority of mobile device operating systems, and is increasingly being used in embedded devices, making it a significant driver of Linux adoption.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The cost to redevelop version 2.6.0 of the Linux kernel in a traditional proprietary development setting has been estimated to be US$612 million (€467M, £394M) in 2004 prices using the COCOMO person-month estimation model.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2006, a study funded by the European Union put the redevelopment cost of kernel version 2.6.8 higher, at €882M ($1.14bn, £744M).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] This topic was revisited in October 2008 by Amanda McPherson, Brian Proffitt, and Ron Hale-Evans.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's methodology, they estimated redevelopment of the 2.6.25 kernel now costs $1.3bn (part of a total $10.8bn to redevelop Fedora 9).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Again, Garcia-Garcia and Alonso de Magdaleno from University of Oviedo (Spain) estimate that the value annually added to kernel was about €100M between 2005 and 2007 and €225M in 2008, it would cost also more than €1bn (about $1.4bn as of February 2010) to develop in the European Union.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As of 7 March 2011, using then-current LOC (lines of code) of a 2.6.x Linux kernel and wage numbers with David A.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's calculations it would cost approximately $3bn (about €2.2bn) to redevelop the Linux kernel as it keeps getting bigger.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] An updated calculation as of 26 September 2018, using then-current 20,088,609 LOC (lines of code) for the 4.14.14 Linux kernel and the current US national average programmer salary of $75,506 show that it would cost approximately $14,725,449,000 (£11,191,341,000) to rewrite the existing code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Most who use Linux do so via a Linux distribution.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Some distributions ship the vanilla or stable kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Several vendors (such as Red Hat and Debian) maintain a customized source tree.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Graph of the sizes of Linux Kernel versions in millions of lines of code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The community of Linux kernel developers comprises about 5000–6000 members.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] According to the "2017 State of Linux Kernel Development", a study issued by the Linux Foundation, covering the commits for the releases 4.8 to 4.13, about 1500 developers were contributing from about 200–250 companies on average.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The top 30 developers contributed a little more than 16% of the code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] For companies, the top contributors are Intel (13.1%) and Red Hat (7.2%), Linaro (5.6%), IBM (4.1%), the second and fifth places are held by the 'none' (8.2%) and 'unknown' (4.1%) categories.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Prominent Linux kernel developers have been aware of the importance of avoiding conflicts between developers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] For a long time there was no code of conduct for kernel developers due to opposition by Torvalds.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] A Linux Kernel *Code of Conflict* was introduced on 8 March 2015.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] It was replaced on 16 September 2018 by a new *Code of Conduct* based on the Contributor Covenant.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] This coincided with a public apology by Torvalds and a brief break from kernel development.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 November 2018, complying with the *Code of Conduct*, Jarkko Sakkinen of Intel sent out patches replacing instances of "fuck" appearing in source code comments with suitable versions focused on the word 'hug'.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Developers who feel treated unfairly can report this to the Linux Foundation Technical Advisory Board.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In July 2013, the maintainer of the USB 3.0 driver Sage Sharp asked Torvalds to address the abusive commentary in the kernel development community.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Sharp backed out of Linux kernel development, saying that "The focus on technical excellence, in combination with overloaded maintainers, and people with different cultural and social norms, means that Linux kernel maintainers are often blunt, rude, or brutal to get their job done".
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] At the linux.conf.au (LCA) conference in 2018, developers expressed the view that the culture of the community has gotten much better in the past few years.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Daniel Vetter, the maintainer of the Intel drm/i915 graphics kernel driver, commented that the "rather violent language and discussion" in the kernel community has decreased or disappeared.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Laurent Pinchart asked developers for feedback on their experiences with the kernel community at the 2017 Embedded Linux Conference Europe.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The issues brought up were discussed a few days later at the Maintainers Summit.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Concerns over the lack of consistency in how maintainers responded to patches submitted by developers were echoed by Shuah Khan, the maintainer of the kernel self-test framework.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds contended that there would never be consistency in the handling of patches because different kernel subsystems have, over time, adopted different development processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, it was agreed upon that each kernel subsystem maintainer would document the rules for patch acceptance.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel source code, a.k.a. source tree, is managed in the Git version control system – also created by Torvalds.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As of 2021, the 5.11 release of the Linux kernel had around 30.34 million lines of code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Roughly 14% of the code is part of the "core," including architecture-specific code, kernel code, and memory management code, while 60% is drivers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Contributions are submitted as patches, in the form of text messages on the Linux kernel mailing list (LKML) (and often also on other mailing lists dedicated to particular subsystems).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The patches must conform to a set of rules and to a formal language that, among other things, describes which lines of code are to be deleted and what others are to be added to the specified files.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] These patches can be automatically processed so that system administrators can apply them in order to make just some changes to the code or to incrementally upgrade to the next version.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is distributed also in GNU zip (gzip) and bzip2 formats.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] A developer who wants to change the Linux kernel writes and tests a code change.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Depending on how significant the change is and how many subsystems it modifies, the change will either be submitted as a single patch or in multiple patches of source code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In case of a single subsystem that is maintained by a single maintainer, these patches are sent as e-mails to the maintainer of the subsystem with the appropriate mailing list in Cc.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer and the readers of the mailing list will review the patches and provide feedback.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Once the review process has finished the subsystem maintainer accepts the patches in the relevant Git kernel tree.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] If the changes to the Linux kernel are bug fixes that are considered important enough, a pull request for the patches will be sent to Torvalds within a few days.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Otherwise, a pull request will be sent to Torvalds during the next merge window.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The merge window usually lasts two weeks and starts immediately after the release of the previous kernel version.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The Git kernel source tree names all developers who have contributed to the Linux kernel in the *Credits* directory and all subsystem maintainers are listed in *Maintainers*.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As with many large open-source software projects, developers are required to adhere to the Contributor Covenant, a code of conduct intended to address harassment of minority contributors.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Additionally, to prevent offense the use of inclusive terminology within the source code is mandated.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is written in a special C programming language supported by GCC, a compiler that extends the C standard in many ways, for example using inline sections of code written in the assembly language (in GCC's "AT&T-style" syntax) of the target architecture.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Initial support for the Rust programming language was added in Linux 6.1, which was released in December 2022, with later kernel versions, such as Linux 6.2 and Linux 6.3, further improving the support.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As for most software, the kernel is versioned as a series of dot-separated numbers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] For early versions, the version consisted of three or four dot-separated numbers called *major release*, *minor release* and *revision.* At that time, odd-numbered minor releases were for development and testing, while even numbered minor releases for production.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The optional fourth digit indicated a patch level.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Development releases were indicated with a release candidate suffix (*-rc*).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The current versioning conventions are different.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The odd/even number implying dev/prod has been dropped, and a major version is indicated by the first two numbers together.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] While the time-frame is open for the development of the next major, the -rcN suffix is used to identify the n'th release candidate for the next version.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] For example, the release of the version 4.16 was preceded by seven 4.16-rcN (from -rc1 to -rc7).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Once a stable version is released, its maintenance is passed to the *stable team*.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Updates to a stable release are identified by a three-number scheme (e.g., 4.16.1, 4.16.2, ...).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is usually built with the GNU toolchain.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU C compiler, GNU cc, part of the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), is the default compiler for mainline Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU Assembler (often called GAS or GNU as) outputs the object files from the GCC generated assembly code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Finally, the GNU Linker (GNU ld) produces a statically linked executable kernel file called vmlinux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Both as and ld are part of GNU Binary Utilities (binutils).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] GNU cc was for a long time the only compiler capable of correctly building Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2004, Intel claimed to have modified the kernel so that its C compiler was also capable of compiling it.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] There was another such reported success in 2009, with a modified 2.6.22 version.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Support for the Intel compiler has been dropped in 2023.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Since 2010, effort has been underway to build Linux with Clang, an alternative compiler for the C language; as of 12 April 2014, the official kernel could almost be compiled by Clang.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The project dedicated to this effort is named *LLVMLinux* after the LLVM compiler infrastructure upon which Clang is built.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] LLVMLinux does not aim to fork either Linux or the LLVM, therefore it is a meta-project composed of patches that are eventually submitted to the upstream projects.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] By enabling Linux to be compiled by Clang, developers may benefit from shorter compilation times.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2017, developers completed upstreaming patches to support building the Linux kernel with Clang in the 4.15 release, having backported support for X86-64 and AArch64 to the 4.4, 4.9, and 4.14 branches of the stable kernel tree.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Google's Pixel 2 shipped with the first Clang built Linux kernel, though patches for Pixel (1st generation) did exist.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] 2018 saw ChromeOS move to building kernels with Clang by default, while Android made Clang and LLVM's linker LLD required for kernel builds in 2019.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Google moved its production kernel used throughout its datacenters to being built with Clang in 2020.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The *ClangBuiltLinux* group coordinates fixes to both Linux and LLVM to ensure compatibility, both composed of members from *LLVMLinux* and having upstreamed patches from *LLVMLinux*.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] As with any software, problems with the Linux kernel can be difficult to troubleshoot.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Common challenges relate to userspace vs. kernel space access, misuse of synchronization primitives, and incorrect hardware management.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] An oops is a non-fatal error in the kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, operations continue with suspect reliability.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] A panic (generated by panic()) is a fatal error.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, the kernel prints a message and halts the computer.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel provides for *debugging by printing* via printk(), which stores messages in a circular buffer (overwriting older entries with newer).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The syslog(2) system call provides for reading and clearing the message buffer and for setting the maximum *log level* of the messages to be sent to the console.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Kernel messages are also exported to userland through the */dev/kmsg* interface.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The *ftrace* mechanism allow for debugging by tracing.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] It is used for monitoring and debugging Linux at runtime and it can analyze user space latencies due to kernel misbehavior.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, *ftrace* allows users to trace Linux at boot-time.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] With KGDB Linux can be debugged in much the same way as userspace programs.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] KGDB requires an additional machine that runs GDB and that is connected to the target to be debugged using a serial cable or Ethernet.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel project integrates new code on a rolling basis.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Standard operating procedure is that software checked into the project must work and compile without error.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Each kernel subsystem is assigned a maintainer who is responsible for reviewing patches against the kernel code standards and keeping a queue of patches that can be submitted to Torvalds within a merge window that is usually several weeks.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Patches are merged by Torvalds into the source code of the prior stable Linux kernel release, creating the release candidate (-rc) for the next stable release.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Once the merge window is closed, only fixes to the new code in the development release are accepted.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The -rc development release of the kernel goes through regression testing and once it is considered stable by Torvalds and the subsystem maintainers, a new version is released and the development process starts over again.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The Git tree that contains the Linux kernel source code is referred to as **mainline Linux**.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Every stable kernel release originates from the mainline tree, and is frequently published on kernel.org.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Mainline Linux has only solid support for a small subset of the many devices that run Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Non-mainline support is provided by independent projects, such as Yocto or Linaro, but in many cases the kernel from the device vendor is needed.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Using a vendor kernel likely requires a board support package.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Maintaining a kernel tree outside of mainline Linux has proven to be difficult.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer of the stable branch, Greg Kroah-Hartman, has applied the term *Linux-like* to downstream kernel forks by vendors that add millions of lines of code to the mainline kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2019, Google stated that it wanted to use the mainline Linux kernel in Android so the number of kernel forks would be reduced.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The term Linux-like has also been applied to the Embeddable Linux Kernel Subset, which does not include the full mainline Linux kernel but a small modified subset of the code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] There are certain communities that develop kernels based on the official Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Some interesting bits of code from these forks that include Linux-libre, Compute Node Linux, INK, L4Linux, RTLinux, and User-Mode Linux (UML) have been merged into the mainline.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Some operating systems developed for mobile phones initially used heavily modified versions of Linux, including Google Android, Firefox OS, HP webOS, Nokia Maemo and Jolla Sailfish OS.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Today Android uses a customized Linux where major changes are implemented in device drivers, but some changes to the core kernel code is required.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Android developers also submit patches to the official Linux that finally can boot the Android operating system.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] For example, a Nexus 7 can boot and run the mainline Linux.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The latest version and older versions are maintained separately.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the latest kernel releases were supervised by Torvalds.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel developer community maintains a stable kernel by applying fixes for software bugs that have been discovered during the development of the subsequent stable kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, www.kernel.org always lists two stable kernels.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] The next stable Linux kernel is released about 8 to 12 weeks later.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Some releases are designated for long-term support as *longterm* with bug fix releases for two or more years.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] Some projects have attempted to reduce the size of the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Josh Triplett started the -tiny source tree for a reduced size version.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Even though seemingly contradictory, the Linux kernel is both monolithic and modular.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is classified as a monolithic kernel architecturally since the entire OS runs in kernel space.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The design is modular since it can be assembled from modules that in some cases are loaded and unloaded at runtime.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] It supports features once only available in closed source kernels of non-free operating systems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The rest of the article makes use of the UNIX and Unix-like operating systems convention of the manual pages.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The number that follows the name of a command, interface, or other feature specifies the section (i.e. the type of the OS' component or feature) it belongs to.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] For example execve(2) refers to a system call, and exec(3) refers to a userspace library wrapper.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The following is an overview of architectural design and of noteworthy features.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Most device drivers and kernel extensions run in kernel space (ring 0 in many CPU architectures), with full access to the hardware.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Some exceptions run in user space; notable examples are filesystems based on FUSE/CUSE, and parts of UIO.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Furthermore, the X Window System and Wayland, the windowing system and display server protocols that most people use with Linux, do not run within the kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Differently, the actual interfacing with GPUs of graphics cards is an in-kernel subsystem called Direct Rendering Manager (DRM).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike standard monolithic kernels, device drivers are easily configured as modules, and loaded or unloaded while the system is running and can also be pre-empted under certain conditions in order to handle hardware interrupts correctly and to better support symmetric multiprocessing.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] By choice, Linux has no stable device driver application binary interface.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux typically makes use of memory protection and virtual memory and can also handle non-uniform memory access, the project has absorbed μClinux, which also makes it possible to run Linux on microcontrollers without virtual memory.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The hardware is represented in the file hierarchy.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] User applications interact with device drivers via entries in the /dev or /sys directories.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Process information is mapped into the /proc directory.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux started as a clone of UNIX, and aims toward POSIX and Single UNIX Specification compliance.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides system calls and other interfaces that are Linux-specific.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In order to be included in the official kernel, the code must comply with a set of licensing rules.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux application binary interface (ABI) between the kernel and the user space has four degrees of stability (stable, testing, obsolete, removed); The system calls are expected to never change in order to preserve compatibility for userspace programs that rely on them.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Loadable kernel modules (LKMs), by design, cannot rely on a stable ABI.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Therefore, they must always be recompiled whenever a new kernel executable is installed in a system, otherwise they will not be loaded.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In-tree drivers that are configured to become an integral part of the kernel executable (vmlinux) are statically linked by the build process.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] There is no guarantee of stability of source-level in-kernel API and, because of this, device driver code, as well as the code of any other kernel subsystem, must be kept updated with kernel evolution.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Any developer who makes an API change is required to fix any code that breaks as the result of their change.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The set of the Linux kernel API that regards the interfaces exposed to user applications is fundamentally composed of UNIX and Linux-specific system calls.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] A system call is an entry point into the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] For example, among the Linux-specific ones there is the family of the clone(2) system calls.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Most extensions must be enabled by defining the `_GNU_SOURCE` macro in a header file or when the user-land code is being compiled.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] System calls can only be invoked via assembly instructions that enable the transition from unprivileged user space to privileged kernel space in ring 0.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] For this reason, the C standard library (libC) acts as a wrapper to most Linux system calls, by exposing C functions that, if needed, transparently enter the kernel, which will execute on behalf of the calling process.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] For system calls not exposed by libC, such as the fast userspace mutex, the library provides a function called syscall(2), which can be used to explicitly invoke them.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Pseudo filesystems (e.g., the sysfs and procfs filesystems) and special files (e.g., `/dev/random`, `/dev/sda`, `/dev/tty`, and many others) constitute another layer of interface to kernel data structures representing hardware or logical (software) devices.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] This issue is mainly due to distribution-specific configurations and a set of patches applied to the code of the Linux kernel, differences in system libraries, services (daemons), filesystem hierarchies, and environment variables.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The main standard concerning application and binary compatibility of Linux distributions is the Linux Standard Base (LSB).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB goes beyond what concerns the Linux kernel, because it also defines the desktop specifications, the X libraries and Qt that have little to do with it.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB version 5 is built upon several standards and drafts (POSIX, SUS, X/Open, File System Hierarchy (FHS), and others).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The standard ABI for how x86_64 user programs invoke system calls is to load the syscall number into the *rax* register, and the other parameters into *rdi*, *rsi*, *rdx*, *r10*, *r8*, and *r9*, and finally to put the *syscall* assembly instruction in the code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] There are several internal kernel APIs between kernel subsystems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux developers chose not to maintain a stable in-kernel ABI.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Modules compiled for a specific version of the kernel cannot be loaded into another version without being recompiled.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux, as other kernels, has the ability to manage processes including creating, suspending, resuming and terminating.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike other operating systems, the Linux kernel implements processes as a group of threads called tasks.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] If two tasks share the same TGID, then they are called in the kernel terminology a task group.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Each task is represented by a *task_struct* data structure.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] A new process can be created by calling clone family of system calls or fork system call.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Processes can be suspended and resumed by the kernel by sending signals like SIGSTOP and SIGCONT.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] A process can terminate itself by calling exit system call, or terminated by another process by sending signals like SIGKILL, SIGABRT or SIGINT.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] If the executable is dynamically linked to shared libraries, a dynamic linker is used to find and load the needed objects, prepare the program to run and then run it.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The Native POSIX Thread Library (NPTL) provides the POSIX standard thread interface (*pthreads*) to userspace.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel isn't aware of processes nor threads but it is aware of *tasks*, thus threads are implemented in userspace.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Threads in Linux are implemented as *tasks* sharing resources, while if they aren't sharing called to be independent processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides the futex(7) (fast user-space mutex) mechanisms for user-space locking and synchronization.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The majority of the operations are performed in userspace but it may be necessary to communicate with the kernel using the futex(2) system call.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] As opposed to userspace threads described above, *kernel threads* run in kernel space.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] They are threads created by the kernel itself for specialized tasks; they are privileged like the kernel and aren't bound to any process or application.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux process scheduler is modular, in the sense that it enables different scheduling classes and policies.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Scheduler classes are pluggable scheduler algorithms that can be registered with the base scheduler code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Each class schedules different types of processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The core code of the scheduler iterates over each class in order of priority and chooses the highest priority scheduler that has a schedulable entity of type struct sched_entity ready to run.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Entities may be threads, group of threads, and even all the processes of a specific user.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux provides both user preemption as well as (selectable, up to) full kernel preemption.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Preemption reduces latency, increases responsiveness, and makes Linux more suitable for desktop and real-time applications.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] This comes at a cost of throughput, as work being interrupted worsens cache behavior.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] For normal tasks, by default, the kernel uses the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) class, introduced in version 2.6.23.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The scheduler is defined as a macro in a C header as `SCHED_NORMAL`.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In other POSIX kernels, a similar policy known as `SCHED_OTHER` allocates CPU timeslices (i.e, it assigns absolute slices of the processor time depending on either predetermined or dynamically computed priority of each process).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] With user preemption, the kernel scheduler can replace the current process with the execution of a context switch to a different one that therefore acquires the computing resources for running (CPU, memory, and more).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] With kernel preemption, the kernel can preempt itself when an interrupt handler returns, when kernel tasks block, and whenever a subsystem explicitly calls the schedule() function.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel also contains two POSIX-compliant real-time scheduling classes named `SCHED_FIFO` (realtime first-in-first-out) and `SCHED_RR` (realtime round-robin), both of which take precedence over the default class.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] An additional scheduling policy known as `SCHED_DEADLINE`, implementing the earliest deadline first algorithm (EDF), was added in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] `SCHED_DEADLINE` takes precedence over all the other scheduling classes.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) scheduler, to prevent the need for CFS "latency nice" patches.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The EEVDF scheduler replaced CFS in version 6.6 of the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel has different causes of concurrency (e.g., interrupts, bottom halves, preemption of kernel and users tasks, symmetrical multiprocessing).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] They consist of atomic types (which can only be manipulated by a set of specific operators), spinlocks, semaphores, mutexes, and lockless algorithms (e.g., RCUs).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Most lock-less algorithms are built on top of memory barriers for the purpose of enforcing memory ordering and prevent undesired side effects due to compiler optimization.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] PREEMPT_RT code included in mainline Linux provide *RT-mutexes*, a special kind of Mutex that do not disable preemption and have support for priority inheritance.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Almost all locks are changed into sleeping locks when using configuration for realtime operation.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Priority inheritance avoids priority inversion by granting a low-priority task that holds a contended lock the priority of a higher-priority waiter until that lock is released.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux includes a kernel lock validator called *Lockdep*.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Although the management of interrupts could be seen as a single job, it is divided into two.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] This split in two is due to the different time constraints and to the synchronization needs of the tasks whose the management is composed of.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The first part is made up of an asynchronous interrupt service routine (ISR) that in Linux is known as the *top half*, while the second part is carried out by one of three types of the so-called *bottom halves* (*softirq*, *tasklets,* and *work queues*).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux interrupt service routines can be nested.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] A new IRQ can trap into a high priority ISR that preempts any other lower priority ISR.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel manages both physical and virtual memory.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] It divides physical memory into zones, each of which has a specific purpose.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Those zones are the most common, but others exist.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux implements virtual memory with 4 or 5-level page tables.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is not pageable (meaning it is always resident in physical memory and cannot be swapped to the disk) and there is no memory protection (no SIGSEGV signals, unlike in user space), therefore memory violations lead to instability and system crashes.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] User memory is pageable by default, although paging for specific memory areas can be disabled with the `mlock()` system call family.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Page frame information is maintained in apposite data structures (of type `struct page`) that are populated immediately after boot and kept until shutdown, regardless of whether they are associated with virtual pages.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The physical address space is divided into different zones, according to architectural constraints and intended use.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] NUMA systems with multiple memory banks are also supported.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Small chunks of memory can be dynamically allocated in kernel space via the family of `kmalloc()` APIs and freed with the appropriate variant of `kfree()`.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] `vmalloc()` and `kvfree()` are used for large virtually contiguous chunks.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] `alloc_pages()` allocates the desired number of entire pages.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel used to include the SLAB, SLUB and SLOB allocators as configurable alternatives.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The SLOB allocator was removed in Linux 6.4 and the SLAB allocator was removed in Linux 6.8.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The sole remaining allocator is SLUB, which aims for simplicity and efficiency, is PREEMPT_RT compatible and was introduced in Linux 2.6.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Since Linux supports numerous filesystems with different features and functionality, it is necessary to implement a generic filesystem that is independent from underlying filesystems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The virtual file system interfaces with other Linux subsystems, userspace, or APIs and abstracts away the different implementations of underlying filesystems.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements system calls like `create`, `open`, `read`, `write` and `close`.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements a generic superblock and inode block that is independent from the one that the underlying filesystem has.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In this subsystem directories and files are represented by a `struct file` data structure.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] When userspace requests access to a file it is returned a file descriptor (non negative integer value) but in kernel space it is a `struct file` structure.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] This structure stores all the information the kernel knows about a file or directory.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] sysfs and procfs are virtual filesystems that expose hardware information and userspace programs' runtime information.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] These filesystems aren't present on disk and instead the kernel implements them as a callback or routine that gets called when they are accessed by userspace.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] While not originally designed to be portable, Linux is now one of the most widely ported operating system kernels, running on a diverse range of systems from the ARM architecture to IBM z/Architecture mainframe computers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The first port was performed on the Motorola 68000 platform.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The modifications to the kernel were so fundamental that Torvalds viewed the Motorola version as a fork and a "Linux-like operating system".
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] That moved Torvalds to lead a major restructure of the code to facilitate porting to more computing architectures.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The first Linux that, in a single source tree, had code for more than i386 alone, supported the DEC Alpha AXP 64-bit platform.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is used as the primary operating system on IBM’s Summit supercomputer.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2019, all systems on the TOP500 list of the world’s fastest supercomputers ran operating systems based on the Linux kernel, whereas the first Linux-based supercomputer appeared on the list in 1998.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux has also been ported to various handheld devices such as iPhone 3G and iPod.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In 2007, the LKDDb project has been started to build a comprehensive database of hardware and protocols known by Linux kernels.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The database is built automatically by static analysis of the kernel sources.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Later in 2014, the Linux Hardware project was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations with the help of users of various Linux distributions.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel updates can be applied without rebooting by using live patching technologies such as Ksplice, kpatch and kGraft.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Initial support for live kernel patching was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in version 4.0, released on 12 April 2015.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The feature, known as *livepatch*, uses the kernel's ftrace functionality and provides a common infrastructure for hot patches supplied through kernel modules, together with interfaces for userspace management tools.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In its initial Linux 4.0 implementation, livepatch support was limited to the x86 architecture and provided basic infrastructure rather than a complete live-patching consistency model.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel bugs present potential security issues.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] For example, they may allow for privilege escalation or create denial-of-service attack vectors.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Over the years, numerous bugs affecting system security were found and fixed.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] New features are frequently implemented to improve the kernel's security.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Capabilities(7) have already been introduced in the section about the processes and threads.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Android makes use of them and systemd gives administrators detailed control over the capabilities of processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux offers a wealth of mechanisms to reduce kernel attack surface and improve security that are collectively known as the Linux Security Modules (LSM).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] They comprise the Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) module, whose code has been originally developed and then released to the public by the NSA, and AppArmor among others.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux is now actively developed and maintained on GitHub.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux and AppArmor provide support to access control security policies, including mandatory access control (MAC), though they profoundly differ in complexity and scope.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Another security feature is the Seccomp BPF (SECure COMPuting with Berkeley Packet Filters), which works by filtering parameters and reducing the set of system calls available to user-land applications.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux distributions typically release security updates to fix vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Many offer long-term support releases that receive security updates for a certain Linux kernel version for an extended period of time.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In 2024, researchers disclosed that the Linux kernel contained a serious vulnerability, CVE-2024-50264, located in the AF_VSOCK subsystem.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] This bug is a use-after-free flaw, a class of memory corruption issue that occurs when a program continues to use memory after it has been freed.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Such flaws are particularly dangerous in the kernel, as they can allow attackers to escalate privileges.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Initially, Torvalds released Linux under a license that forbade any commercial use.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] This was changed in version 0.12 by a switch to the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] This license allows distribution and sale of possibly modified and unmodified versions of Linux but requires that all those copies be released under the same license and be accompanied by - or that, on request, free access is given to - the complete corresponding source code.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds has described licensing Linux under the GPLv2 as the "best thing I ever did".
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel is licensed explicitly under GNU General Public License version 2 only (GPL-2.0-only) with an explicit syscall exception (Linux-syscall-note), without offering the licensee the option to choose any later version, which is a common GPL extension.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Contributed code must be available under GPL-compatible license.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] There was considerable debate about how easily the license could be changed to use later GPL versions (including version 3), and whether this change is even desirable.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds himself specifically indicated upon the release of version 2.4.0 that his own code is released only under version 2.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The terms of the GPL state that if no version is specified, then any version may be used, and Alan Cox pointed out that very few other Linux contributors had specified a particular version of the GPL.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In September 2006, a survey of 29 key kernel programmers indicated that 28 preferred GPLv2 to the then-current GPLv3 draft.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] They referred to clauses regarding DRM/tivoization, patents, "additional restrictions" and warned a Balkanisation of the "Open Source Universe" by the GPLv3.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds, who decided not to adopt the GPLv3 for the Linux kernel, reiterated his criticism even years later.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] It is debated whether some loadable kernel modules (LKMs) are to be considered derivative works under copyright law, and thereby whether or not they fall under the terms of the GPL.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In accordance with the license rules, LKMs using only a public subset of the kernel interfaces are non-derived works, thus Linux gives system administrators the mechanisms to load out-of-tree binary objects into the kernel address space.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] There are some out-of-tree loadable modules that make legitimate use of the *dma_buf* kernel feature.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] GPL compliant code can certainly use it.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] A different possible use case would be Nvidia Optimus that pairs a fast GPU with an Intel integrated GPU, where the Nvidia GPU writes into the Intel framebuffer when it is active.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] But, Nvidia cannot use this infrastructure because it necessitates bypassing a rule that can only be used by LKMs that are also GPL.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Alan Cox replied on LKML, rejecting a request from one of Nvidia's engineers to remove this technical enforcement from the API.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds clearly stated on the LKML that "[I] claim that binary-only kernel modules ARE derivative "by default"'".
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] On the other hand, Torvalds has also said that "[one] gray area in particular is something like a driver that was originally written for another operating system (i.e., clearly not a derived work of Linux in origin).
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] THAT is a gray area, and _that_ is the area where I personally believe that some modules may be considered to not be derived works simply because they weren't designed for Linux and don't depend on any special Linux behaviour".
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Proprietary graphics drivers, in particular, are heavily discussed.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Whenever proprietary modules are loaded into Linux, the kernel marks itself as being "tainted", and therefore bug reports from tainted kernels will often be ignored by developers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] The official kernel, that is, Torvalds's git branch at the kernel.org repository, contains binary blobs released under the terms of the GNU GPLv2 license.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux can also load binary blobs, proprietary firmware, drivers, or other executable modules from the filesystem, and link them into kernel space.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is a registered trademark of Linus Torvalds in the United States, the European Union, and some other countries.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] A legal battle over the trademark began in 1996, when William Della Croce, a lawyer who was never involved in the development of Linux, started requesting licensing fees for the use of the word *Linux*.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] After it was proven that the word was in common use long before Della Croce's claimed first use, the trademark was awarded to Torvalds.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2024, during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, kernel developer Greg Kroah-Hartman removed some kernel developers whose email addresses suggested a connection to Russia from their roles as maintainers.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] Linus Torvalds responded that he did not support Russian aggression and would not revert the patch, insinuating that opponents of the patch were Russian trolls.
[src:linux-capabilities/linux-kernel-p02] James Bottomley, a kernel developer, issued an apology for the handling of the situation and clarified that the action was a consequence of U.S. sanctions against Russia.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:linux-capabilities/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] In Unix-like systems, the access rights flags **setuid** and **setgid** (short for *set user identity* and *set group identity*) allow users to run an executable with the file system permissions of the executable's owner or group respectively and to change behaviour in directories.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] They are often used to allow users on a computer system to run programs with temporarily elevated privileges to perform a specific task.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] While the assumed user id or group id privileges provided are not always elevated, at a minimum they are specific.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] The flags `setuid` and `setgid` are needed for tasks that require different privileges than what the user is normally granted, such as the ability to alter system files or databases to change their login password.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Some of the tasks that require additional privileges may not immediately be obvious, though, such as the `ping` command, which must send and listen for control packets on a network interface.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] The `setuid` and `setgid` flags have different effects, depending on whether they are applied to a file, to a directory or binary executable or non-binary executable file.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] The `setuid` and `setgid` flags have an effect only on binary executable files and not on scripts (e.g., Bash, Perl, Python).
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] This allows the system designer to permit trusted programs to be run which a user would otherwise not be allowed to execute.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] For example, the ping command may need access to networking privileges that a normal user cannot access; therefore it may be given the setuid flag to ensure that a user who needs to ping another system can do so, even if their account does not have the required privilege for sending packets.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] While the `setuid` feature is very useful in many cases, its improper use can pose a security risk if the `setuid` attribute is assigned to executable programs that are not carefully designed.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Due to potential security issues, many operating systems ignore the `setuid` attribute when applied to executable *shell scripts*.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] The presence of `setuid` executables explains why the `chroot` system call is not available to non-root users on Unix.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] See limitations of `chroot` for more details.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Setting the `setgid` permission on a directory causes files and subdirectories created within to inherit its group ownership, rather than the primary group of the file-creating process.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Created subdirectories also inherit the `setgid` bit.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] The policy is only applied during creation and, thus, only prospectively.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Directories and files existing when the `setgid` bit is applied are unaffected, as are directories and files moved into the directory on which the bit is set.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] This allows a group of users to work with files without explicitly setting permissions, but limited by the security model expectation that existing files permissions do not implicitly change.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] This is generally not needed on most systems derived from BSD, since by default directories are treated as if their `setgid` bit is always set, regardless of the actual value.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] On FreeBSD, setting the `setuid` bit on a directory on a UFS file system mounted with the suiddir option causes files and subdirectories created within to inherit its ownership, rather than the user ID of the file-creating process.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Executables on which these bits are set must be designed and implemented carefully to avoid security vulnerabilities including buffer overruns and path injection.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Successful buffer-overrun attacks on vulnerable applications allow the attacker to execute arbitrary code under the rights of the process exploited.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] In the event that a vulnerable process uses the `setuid` bit to run as `root`, the code will execute with root privileges, in effect giving the attacker root access to the system on which the vulnerable process is running.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] Of particular importance in the case of a `setuid` or `setgid` process is the environment of the process.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] If the environment is not properly sanitized by a privileged process, its behavior can be changed by the unprivileged process that started it.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] For example, GNU libc was at one point vulnerable to an exploit using `setuid` and an environment variable that allowed executing code from untrusted shared libraries.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] The `setuid` bit was invented by Dennis Ritchie and was in the first version of Unix.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] His employer, then Bell Telephone Laboratories, applied for a patent in 1972.
[src:linux-capabilities/setuid] The patent was granted in 1979 as patent number US 4135240 "Protection of data file contents", and was dedicated to the public domain in the same year.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Unlike the similar command `su`, users must, by default, supply their own password for authentication, rather than the password of the target user.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] After authentication, and if the configuration file (typically `/etc/sudoers`) permits the user access, the system invokes the requested command.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] The configuration file offers detailed access permissions, including enabling commands only from the invoking terminal; requiring a password per user or group; requiring re-entry of a password every time or never requiring a password at all for a particular command line.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] It can also be configured to permit passing arguments or multiple commands.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] In November 2009, Thomas Claburn, in response to concerns that Microsoft had patented sudo, characterized such suspicions as overblown.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] The claims were narrowly framed to a particular GUI, rather than to the sudo concept.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] The logo is a reference to an xkcd strip, where an order for a sandwich is accepted only when preceded with `sudo`.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Unlike for `su`, users supply their personal password to `sudo` (if necessary) rather than that of the superuser or other account.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] This allows authorized users to exercise altered privileges without compromising the secrecy of the other account's password.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Users must be in a certain group to use the `sudo` command, typically either the *wheel* or *sudo* group.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] After authentication, and if the configuration file permits the user access, the system invokes the requested command.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] `sudo` retains the user's invocation rights through a grace period (typically 5 minutes) per pseudo terminal, allowing the user to execute several successive commands as the requested user without having to provide a password again.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] As a security and auditing feature, `sudo` may be configured to log each command run.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] When a user attempts to invoke `sudo` without being listed in the configuration file, an exception indication is presented to the user indicating that the attempt has been recorded.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] If configured, the root user will be alerted via mail.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] By default, an entry is recorded in the system.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] The `/etc/sudoers` file contains a list of users or user groups with permission to execute a subset of commands while having the privileges of the root user or another specified user.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] The file can be edited by using the command `sudo visudo`.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Sudo contains several configuration options such as allowing commands to be run as `sudo` without a password, changing which users can use `sudo`, and changing the message displayed upon entering an incorrect password.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Sudo features an easter egg that can be enabled from the configuration file that will display an insult every time an incorrect password is entered.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] In some system distributions, `sudo` has largely supplanted the default use of a distinct superuser login for administrative tasks, most notably in some Linux distributions as well as Apple's macOS.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] This allows for more secure logging of admin commands and prevents some exploits.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] In association with SELinux, `sudo` can be used to transition between roles in role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Sudoedit is a program that symlinks to the sudo binary.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] When sudo is run via its sudoedit alias, sudo behaves as if the -e flag has been passed and allows users to edit files that require additional privileges to write to.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Microsoft released its own tool also called `sudo` for Windows in February 2024.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Its interface is similar to its Unix counterpart by giving the ability to run elevated commands from an unelevated console session, although its implementation is entirely different.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] The program runas provides comparable functionality in Windows, but it cannot pass current directories, environment variables or long command lines to the child.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] And while it supports running the child as another user, it does not support simple elevation.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Hamilton C shell also includes true `su` and `sudo` for Windows that can pass all of that state information and start the child either elevated or as another user (or both).
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Graphical user interfaces exist for sudo – notably *gksudo* – but are deprecated in Debian and no longer included in Ubuntu.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] Other user interfaces are not directly built on sudo, but provide similar temporary privilege elevation for administrative purposes, such as pkexec in Unix-like operating systems, User Account Control in Microsoft Windows and Mac OS X Authorization Services.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] doas, available since OpenBSD 5.8 (October 2015), has been written in order to replace `sudo` in the OpenBSD base system, with the latter still being made available as a port.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] gosu is a tool similar to sudo that is popular in containers where the terminal may not be fully functional or where there are undesirable effects from running sudo in a containerized environment.
[src:linux-capabilities/sudo] A rewrite of sudo, called sudo-rs, written in the Rust programming language, became adopted as the default in Ubuntu.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In computing, the **superuser** is a special user account used for system administration.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Depending on the operating system (OS), the actual name of this account might be **root**, **administrator**, **admin** or **supervisor**.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] The principle of least privilege recommends that most users and applications run under an ordinary account to perform their work, as a superuser account is capable of making unrestricted, potentially adverse, system-wide changes.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In some cases, the actual name of the account determines whether the user is a superuser.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In Unix-like computer OSes (such as Linux), *root* is the conventional name of the user who has all rights or permissions (to all files and programs) in all modes (single- or multi-user).
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Alternative names include *baron* in BeOS and *avatar* on some Unix variants.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] BSD often provides a *toor* ("root" written backward) account in addition to a root account.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Regardless of the name, the superuser always has a user ID of 0.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] The root user can do many things an ordinary user cannot, such as changing the ownership of files and binding to network ports numbered below 1024.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] The name *root* may have originated because *root* is the only user account with permission to modify the root directory of a Unix system.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] This directory was originally considered to be root's home directory, but the UNIX Filesystem Hierarchy Standard now recommends that root's home be at /root.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] The first process bootstrapped in a Unix-like system, usually called init, runs with root privileges.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] It spawns all other processes directly or indirectly, which inherit their parents' privileges.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Only a process running as root is allowed to change its user ID to that of another user; once it has done so, there is no way back.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Doing so is sometimes called *dropping root privileges* and is often done as a security measure to limit the damage from possible contamination of the process.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Another case is login and other programs that ask users for credentials and in case of successful authentication allow them to run programs with privileges of their accounts.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] It is often recommended that *root* is never used as a normal user account, since simple typographical errors in entering commands can cause major damage to the system.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Instead, a normal user account should be used, and then either the su (substitute user) or sudo (substitute user do) command is used.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] The su approach requires the user to know the root password, while the sudo method requires that the user be set up with the power to run "as root" within the /etc/sudoers file, typically indirectly by being made a member of the *wheel*, *adm*, *admin*, or *sudo* group.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] For a number of reasons, the sudo approach is now generally preferred – for example it leaves an audit trail of who has used the command and what administrative operations they performed.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Some OSes, such as macOS and some Linux distributions (most notably Ubuntu), automatically give the initial user created the ability to run as root via sudo – but this is configured to ask them for their password before doing administrative actions.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In some cases the actual *root* account is disabled by default, so it can't be directly used.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In mobile platform-oriented OSs such as Apple iOS and Android, superuser access is inaccessible by design, but generally the security system can be exploited in order to obtain it.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In a few systems, such as Plan 9, there is no superuser at all.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In Windows XP and earlier systems, there is a built-in administrator account that remains hidden when a user administrator-equivalent account exists.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] This built-in administrator account is created with a blank password.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] This poses security risks as local users would be able to access the computer via the built-in administrator account if the password is left blank, so the account is disabled by default in Windows Vista and later systems due to the introduction of User Account Control (UAC).
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Remote users are unable to access the built-in administrator account.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] A Windows administrator account is not an exact analogue of the Unix root account – Administrator, the built-in administrator account, and a user administrator account have the same level of privileges.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] The default user account created in Windows systems is an administrator account.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Unlike macOS, Linux, and Windows Vista/7/8/10 administrator accounts, administrator accounts in Windows systems without UAC do not insulate the system from most of the pitfalls of full root access.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] One of these pitfalls includes decreased resilience to malware infections.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] To avoid this and maintain optimal system security on pre-UAC Windows systems, it is recommended to simply authenticate when necessary from a standard user account, either via a password set to the built-in administrator account, or another administrator account.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In Windows Vista/7/8/10/11 administrator accounts, a prompt will appear to authenticate running a process with elevated privileges.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Usually, no user credentials are required to authenticate the UAC prompt in administrator accounts but authenticating the UAC prompt requires entering the username and password of an administrator in standard user accounts.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In Windows XP (and earlier systems) administrator accounts, authentication is not required to run a process with elevated privileges.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] This poses a security risk that led to the development of UAC.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Users can set a process to run with elevated privileges from standard accounts by setting the process to "run as administrator" or using the runas command and authenticating the prompt with credentials (username and password) of an administrator account.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Even with Administrator access, some system files are protected by even higher elevated system accounts, namely *SYSTEM* and *NT Service/TrustedInstaller* which are analogous to Linux *root* user.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In Windows NT, 2000 and higher, the root user is the Administrator account.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In Novell NetWare, the superuser was called "supervisor", later "admin".
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] In OpenVMS, "SYSTEM" is the superuser account for the OS.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] On most personal computers from the 1970s and 1980s, anyone using the system has full privileges, and there is no concept of user accounts.
[src:linux-capabilities/superuser] Windows 95 allows multiple accounts, so that each can have its own preferences profile; each user still has full administrative control over the machine.
